column3: LKHC: Stage 6 - Mix Canyon (Home of the steepest Mile in CA)
column5: After about 3 miles the steepest mile in CA is ahead of you (Avg 15.8%, around 24% near the top), and I survived, with a standard double crank! No, I didn't set any records, and I was pretty much going back and forth to lessen the grade, until the really steep part, then i stood up and just pushed through. Was a touch climb for sure, but it wasn't quite as bad as I imagined. I also got a goat-head thorn in my front tire right as I started warming up, so i had to go throw in another tube. http://www.toughascent.com/blog/?p=224
Was planning on riding up mill creek, but about a mile of the way up i got a slow flat, so I pumped air and decided to turn back and go home. :-( So I went for a run after.

I missed the actual race because I had to take my dog to the emergency room (she's okay now), so I wanted to ride it, because I was planning to ride it anyway with the LKHC series so I could be in the 100% club, so now I am in my own eyes, also there is a virtual low key on Strava, So now I'm in that 100% club

column3: LKHC Stage 8 - Kings Mountain (+ Beast Ride(at least for me))
column5: This was my hardest ride to date, I've never climbed this much during a ride. I first rode easy to the LKHC meet up spot at Edgewood and Canada. Right when I got there, I noticed my front tire was flat, so I replaced the tube and waited for the ride to the start to begin. From there we rode to Greer and Kings Mt where we started. The climb wasn't so bad, it's a fairly easy climb compared to other in the area. 200 paces before the finish I gave it all I had (but stayed seated) and my hamstrings started cramping, but I finished strong. I stretched at the top, ate a banana and an energy bar, the continued on, south on Skyline. By the time I got to the vista point about a mile before Pagemill my quads were starting to cramp pretty bad, so i decided i should probably rest, and eat more. I ate an apple and half of another energy bar, and finished off my Gatorade, stretched again, then continued on, still south on skyline Once i passed Pagemill I was in new territory (because I've never ridden this part of skyline), finally after a total of 20 miles on skyline I came to Hwy 9, I descended towards Saratoga (easy) and had planned on continuing down Redwood Gulch, but missed it, and didn't realize that until i was about a mile past, so I turned back, heading back up hwy 9, and almost immediately my quads started cramping again, so i got off my bike and could barely stand, so I sat there squatting on the side of the road for a minute or so, then stretched again, and ate the rest of my energy bar and drank a lot of water, rested for about 10 more minutes, and felt better, so I continued on, back up hwy 9. Finally i came to Redwood Gulch (not soon enough), descended it to the end of the road, and continued descending down Stevens creek until it turned to Foothill and took that back to Palo Alto.

Wanted to do an easy ride before race day, and i've never ridden here, so Tim showed me the trail, it's very nice scenery. We did an out and back. Tim got a flat on our way back, so we had to stop to fix it, good thing we had our lights, cause it was dark.

Happy Thanksgiving. This was my first time ever riding up this road, it is defiantly the longest climb I've done, and also it's the highest I've ever been on my bike! It wasn't too bad going up, the road never gets too steep, but I had to pace myself, because if I pushed too hard in the beginning of the climb I would be hurting really bad at the end. I ate a few energy bars and raisins and drank a bunch of Gatorade to keep the carb intake constant so my muscles had energy to burn. Probably the last 3 or 4 miles before the top it started getting really foggy and I couldn't see very far, it was a really heavy fog. while at the top it seemed to be getting worse. I stayed at the top for about 30 minutes, then was ready to descend. I didn't really realize how long the road was until the descent, it seemed like it was never ending, and the fog was so heavy it was basically sprinkling, and going 20-30MPH sprinkles feel like rain, and it was like that all the way down, I was soaked by the bottom, even my socks were wet, I could feel the water squishing in my shoes every time I pedaled. It was really cold at the top, but by the time I got down to about 2500ft it got warmer, and my hands began thawing.
I think I pressed the wrong button when i started the ride, so it didn't start recording until about a half mile after turning onto Arastradero Rd, but right before entering the preserve.
